y argues that the concepts of leadership and public morality in the major Asian traditions offer a valuable perspective on humanizing the globalization process. Turning to the classic ideals of the Buddhist, Hindu, Confucian, and Japanese traditions, he investigates the nature of true leadership and its relation to learning, virtue, and education in human governance; the role in society of the public intellectual; and the responsibilities of those in power in creating and maintaining civil society. De Bary recognizes that throughout history ideals have always come up against messy human complications. Still, he finds in the exploration and affirmation of common values a worthy attempt to grapple with persistent human dilemmas across the globe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aCivil societyxHistoryxAsia. 0aCivil societyzAsiaxHistory. 0aLeadershipxAspect religieuxxBouddhismexChinaxIndienxJapan. 0aLeadershipxAspect religieuxxConfucianisme. 0aLeadershipxAspect religieuxxHindouisme. 0aLeadershipxHistoirexAsie. 0aLeadershipxHistoryxAsia. 0aLeadershipxReligious aspectsxBuddhism. 0aLeadershipxReligious aspectsxConfucianism. 0aLeadershipxReligious aspectsxHinduism. 0aLeadershipzAsiaxHistory. 0aSociété civilexHistoirexAsie. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674030671zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674030671423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674030671/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK